{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:36:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:36:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16428"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16428"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.22,0.05,0.07,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16428"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95393"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4554"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46337"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with vaginal bleeding and cramping abdominal pain. She is eight weeks pregnant by her last menstrual period. The bleeding started two days ago and was initially heavy with large clots but has now settled to light spotting. The cramping pain has also largely resolved. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. She has had one previous uncomplicated pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Speculum examination reveals a closed cervical os with minimal dark blood in the vaginal vault. Transvaginal ultrasound shows an empty uterus with endometrial thickness of 8 mm. Serum beta-human chorionic gonadotropin is 150 IU/L (\u0026gt;2000 for viable pregnancy at 8 weeks).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Misoprostol 800 micrograms per vagina","Repeat beta-human chorionic gonadotropin in 48 hours","Urgent referral to Early Pregnancy Assessment Unit","Surgical evacuation of retained products","Conservative management with follow-up in one week"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture consistent with a complete miscarriage. The initial heavy bleeding and cramping followed by resolution of symptoms, combined with an empty uterus on ultrasound with thin endometrium (\u0026lt;15mm) and low beta-human chorionic gonadotropin (bHCG) levels are diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management with follow-up in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as the miscarriage appears complete, the patient is haemodynamically stable, and there are no signs of complications. The follow-up visit allows assessment of ongoing symptoms and provides an opportunity for emotional support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical evacuation of retained products\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary when ultrasound confirms an empty uterus with thin endometrium. This procedure would expose the patient to unnecessary surgical risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E is used for medical management of incomplete miscarriage or missed miscarriage. It is not indicated when the miscarriage is already complete.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat beta-human chorionic gonadotropin\u003C/strong\u003E testing is not necessary when ultrasound confirms a complete miscarriage. Serial bHCG measurements are more useful in cases of pregnancy of unknown location or suspected ectopic pregnancy. Whilst an ectopic pregnancy cannot be excluded with a single BHCG - taking the clinical context into consideration in this case, a complete miscarriage is the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent referral to Early Pregnancy Assessment Unit\u003C/strong\u003E is not required as this is a complete miscarriage without complications. These units are more appropriate for cases requiring ongoing assessment such as threatened miscarriage or pregnancy of unknown location.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete miscarriage can be diagnosed when bleeding and pain have settled, and ultrasound shows an empty uterus with endometrial thickness \u003C15mm.","Conservative management with follow-up is appropriate for complete miscarriage if the patient is haemodynamically stable and wishes to avoid intervention."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Pregnancy loss [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Pregnancy-Loss.pdf","Queensland Health. Guideline: Early pregnancy loss [Internet]. Brisbane: Queensland Health; 2021 [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0033/139947/g-epl.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16428"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-11T19:57:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T19:58:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1540"},"attr